    "title": "Deed Fraud",
    "url": "https://pasenatorsaval.com/tth/deed-fraud/",
    "date": null,
    "raw_text": "Deed Fraud\nDeed Fraud\nOctober 24, 2023\nhttps://pasenatorsaval.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/TTH-Deed-Fraud-Oct-24-2023.mp3\nOn Tuesday, October 24, Senator Saval hosted a telephone town hall on DEED FRAUD.\nDeed fraud occurs when a person sells a home by pretending to be the legal owner without having ever received the owner’s permission. This is becoming a serious issue in our city, robbing people not only of their property, but their safety and stability.\nFortunately, protecting your home and the homes of your loved ones from would-be scammers is simple and easy when you know where to go and what to do. At this telephone town hall, James Leonard, Commissioner of Records of the City of Philadelphia, shared the steps that Philly homeowners can take to safeguard their homes and what to do if they suspect they are being targeted or that deed fraud has occurred.\nListen to the recording of the town hall above, and check out these resources from Commissioner Leonard to keep your home safe:\nGet help with deed fraud\nGet a copy of your deed\nRecord a deed\nGet a copy of public safety reports (traffic, police incidents, fire reports and emergency medical services reports)\nView proposed City regulations\nOpt out of aggressive real estate solicitation\nTo join our\nnext\nconversation, please complete the form below and we will call you before the event starts. You can also come back here to listen in online. Please note that you must sign up by noon on the day of the event to be included.\nPlease select a valid form\nNewsroom\n→ Press Releases\n→ Video\n→ Audio\n→ Newsletters\n→ Media Mentions\n→ Media Requests\n→ Photo Gallery\n→ Upcoming Events",
    "ai_summary": {
      "summary": "Senator Saval hosted a telephone town hall on October 24, 2023, focused on deed fraud, a scam in which someone illegally sells a home they don't own. Philadelphia's Commissioner of Records, James Leonard, participated to explain how homeowners can protect themselves and what steps to take if they suspect fraud. The release includes links to city resources for residents.",
