  {
    "title": "Senate Democrats Highlight Housing Legislation to Deliver Safe, Affordable Housing to Every Pennsylvanian",
    "url": "https://pasenatorsaval.com/senate-democrats-highlight-housing-legislation-to-deliver-safe-affordable-housing-to-every-pennsylvanian/",
    "date": null,
    "raw_text": "Senate Democrats Highlight Housing Legislation to Deliver Safe, Affordable Housing to Every Pennsylvanian\nJune 24, 2026\nHARRISBURG, PA − June 24, 2026 −\nMembers of the\nPennsylvania Senate Democratic Caucus\ngathered in the Main Capitol Rotunda today to champion bills, initiatives, and investments that will bring down the cost of housing for Pennsylvanians and empower renters.\n“As the cost of housing and utilities continue to climb and burden Pennsylvania’s working families, Senate Democrats are keenly focused on fighting for a safe, affordable place to call home for every Pennsylvanian,”\nsaid Senate Democratic Leader Jay Costa\n. “Senate Democrats have been leading the way in the housing space, and we continue to advocate strongly for our colleagues across the aisle to join us in tackling the housing crisis facing our Commonwealth.”\nSenators drew attention to the myriad successes the caucus has secured in the housing space over the past few years, including the creation of the Housing Opportunities Program, dramatic increases in funding to the Pennsylvania Housing Finance Agency, the creation of the Whole Home Repairs Program, and the passage of a Pittsburgh Longterm Owner Occupant Tax Exemption Program (LOOP).\nHowever, despite these successes, Pennsylvania continues to lack the necessary affordable housing stock to ensure a safe, affordable home for every Pennsylvanian. As a part of the Governor’s Housing Action Plan,\nthe Department of Community and Economic Development\nestimates\nthat Pennsylvania will need to build 450,000 new housing units by 2035 to meet projected demand, but without a change in the rate of construction, will fall short by nearly 185,000 homes. Additionally, renters and manufactured homeowners continue to face skyrocketing costs and fees with hardly any legal protection from exploitation.\nAs of this morning,\nPresident Trump is withholding his signature from the 21\nst\nCentury ROAD to Housing Bill\n, a landmark, bipartisan affordable housing bill in an attempt to disenfranchise millions of voters and rig future elections in his party’s favor.\nAs such, Senate Democrats highlighted bills at the state level that would remove barriers to homeownership, increase Pennsylvania’s affordable housing stock, and support renters. Some of those bills include:\nSB 549\n, which would seal or limit access to eviction records for PA tenants\nSB 1203\n, which would tackle “tangled titles” and remove barriers to homeownership\nSB 294\n, which would remove the cap on housing projects currently in the Redevelopment Assistance Capital Program (RACP) law, allowing the program to better support the housing needs of the Commonwealth and make significant progress on closing our housing unit gap.\nSB 746\n, which would protect residents of manufactured home communities from unjustified lot rent and fee increases, especially from private equity companies\n“Affordable housing is really at the core of Pennsylvania’s affordability crisis,”\nsaid Senator Vincent Hughes.\n“Senate Democrats understand the need and we have solutions. Now it’s time for Senate Republicans to join us in getting those solutions over the finish line. We have the opportunity to lift up entire communities by securing these affordable housing investments and implementing commonsense policies that protect our homeowners.”\n“The need for action is clear and urgent: hundreds of thousands of Pennsylvania homes are estimated to need critical repairs, and nearly 17,000 people remain on program waitlists,”\nsaid Senator Nikil Saval.\n“Add on top utility bills and insurance rates, and it’s no wonder so many homeowners are struggling to afford repairs. The Pennsylvania Home Preservation Program is a major step toward disrupting the ongoing cycle of unaffordability and disrepair, speculation, and community displacement. We need to move this bill, pass it, and fund it for years to come.”\n“Housing is a cause of angst for everyone from young families to seniors. No sector of our housing market is immune from steep price increases, including manufactured home communities,”\nsaid Senator Judy Schwank.\n“We have commonsense proposals to protect manufactured homeowners, most of whom are seniors, veterans, and folks with disabilities, from price gouging. This budget is a tremendous opportunity to take action and show Pennsylvanians that we are serious about finding solutions to our housing crisis.”\n“One of the most important ways we can address the housing crisis is by cutting red tape and removing barriers to home ownership,”\nsaid Senator James Malone\n. “I introduced SB 1203 to help counties streamline small property title changes to help families of modest means more easily establish legal ownership of homes passed down to them. I’m proud to present this alongside Governor Shapiro and my colleagues’ other proposals, which will work on the housing crisis from multiple angles.”\nLearn more about how Senate Democrats are fighting for safe, affordable homes for every Pennsylvanian at\nPASenate.com/Housing\n.\n######",
    "ai_summary": {
      "summary": "Pennsylvania Senate Democrats held a press event in the Capitol Rotunda to promote a package of state-level housing bills they have introduced, including measures to seal eviction records, address title issues for inherited homes, expand a capital program for housing projects, and protect manufactured home residents from rent increases. The senators called on Senate Republicans to pass the bills and tied their efforts to a broader housing shortage estimated at 185,000 units by 2035. No new legislation was passed at this event.",
      "action_type": "statement",
      "topics": [
        "housing",
        "economy"
      ],
      "spin_flag": true
    }
  },
  {
    "title": "Advocates Call for Transit Funding in the 2026–2027 PA State Budget",
    "url": "https://pasenatorsaval.com/advocates-call-for-transit-funding-in-the-2026-2027-pa-state-budget/",
    "date": null,
    "raw_text": "Advocates Call for Transit Funding in the 2026–2027 PA State Budget\nJune 26, 2026\nRiders, advocates, and elected officials gather at the El stop at 5th and Market Streets near Philadelphia’s Independence Mall to call for full transit funding in the 2026–2027 state budget.\nPHILADELPHIA, PA − June 26, 2026 −\nToday, transit advocates, community leaders, and elected representatives gathered near Independence Mall to call for funding in the 2026–2027 Pennsylvania state budget to keep transit systems moving across the Commonwealth.\n“Creating new, dedicated revenue sources for the services that move nearly a million Pennsylvanians each day is possible, necessary, and urgent,”\nsaid Julio Rodriguez, Policy Director for the Bicycle Coalition of Greater Philadelphia\n. “People should be able to walk, bike, and take public transit to their destination, it’s how we get to less cars on the road.”\nPHILADELPHIA, PA − June 26, 2026 −\nToday, transit advocates, community leaders, and elected representatives gathered near Independence Mall to call for funding in the 2026–2027 Pennsylvania state budget to keep transit systems moving across the Commonwealth.\nTransit operates in every county in Pennsylvania, with nearly a million people across the Commonwealth utilizing public transit each day.\n“Transit plays a vital role in the 6th Senatorial District and throughout Pennsylvania, providing essential transportation for residents, students, seniors, individuals with disabilities, and our workforce. Reliable public transit connects people to jobs, schools, healthcare, and countless other opportunities, while also supporting our regional economy,”\nsaid State Senator Frank Farry (R–Bucks)\n. “When transit agencies faced a significant financial crisis last year, my colleagues and I worked tirelessly to identify a short-term solution to prevent service disruptions. However, from the beginning, our focus has always been on developing a sustainable, long-term funding strategy that provides certainty for transit agencies and the people who depend on them every day.”\nThe El stop at 5th and Market Streets was recently renovated with modern facilities, including new elevators and ramps to allow riders with disabilities and those traveling with strollers, market carts, and bicycles to access transit and get where they need to go. Speakers noted the need for crucial infrastructure upgrades for bus, train, and trolley stops across Pennsylvania.\n“Our transit is what brought the World Cup to Philadelphia. Our transit is what allows us to prepare for the MLB All-Star festivities. Our transit is helping millions visit our city and celebrate the 250th anniversary of the signing of the Declaration of Independence. And this is on top of the fact that transit helps hundreds of thousands of people throughout the region get where we need to go each and every day,”\nsaid State Senator Nikil Saval (D–Philadelphia)\n. “The Pennsylvania legislature can ensure freedom of movement for everyone who lives, works, and visits Pennsylvania by coming together and prioritizing transit.”\n“Public transit is essential to the economic strength and daily life of communities across Pennsylvania. Last year, I walked 105 miles from North Philadelphia to Harrisburg to raise awareness about the urgent need for reliable, long-term transit funding,” said\nState\nRepresentative Malcolm Kenyatta (D–Philadelphia).\n“Public transit is not a luxury—it is a lifeline connecting people to work, school, medical care, and opportunity. Riders should not have to face another crisis before Harrisburg acts. Pennsylvania moves when public transit moves, and it is time for the state to fund it like the essential public service it is.”\n“Nearly every transit agency in PA has been forced to\nrob its fixed-route budgets\nto keep essential shared-ride and paratransit services running—endangering the long-term health of fixed-route services in the process,”\nsaid Connor Descheemaker, statewide campaign manager for Transit For All PA\n. “This has positioned our most vulnerable residents, in the most rural corners of the state, on the brink of losing access to healthcare, food, jobs, and community. Now, with a budget due and new revenue sources possible, transit funding must be a top priority. Alongside a new funding model for shared-ride and paratransit services in all 67 counties, we can deliver new revenue for our entire Commonwealth.”\nThe Pennsylvania state budget for 2026–2026 is due to be passed by Wednesday, July 1.",
    "ai_summary": {
      "summary": "Elected officials, transit advocates, and community leaders held a rally near Philadelphia's Independence Mall to urge Pennsylvania lawmakers to include dedicated, long-term public transit funding in the 2026–2027 state budget, which is due by July 1. Speakers highlighted that transit agencies across all 67 Pennsylvania counties are facing financial strain, with some diverting fixed-route funds to cover paratransit costs. No legislation was introduced or passed at the event; it was a public advocacy gathering ahead of budget negotiations.",
      "action_type": "statement",
      "topics": [
        "infrastructure",
        "economy",
        "other"
      ],
      "spin_flag": false
    }
  },
  {
    "title": "“A Budget of Missed Opportunity”: Senator Saval’s Statement on the 2026–2027 PA State Budget",
    "url": "https://pasenatorsaval.com/a-budget-of-missed-opportunity-senator-savals-statement-on-the-2026-2027-pa-state-budget/",
    "date": null,
    "raw_text": "“A Budget of Missed Opportunity”: Senator Saval’s Statement on the 2026–2027 PA State Budget\nJuly 13, 2026\nWhile making several important investments that will benefit Pennsylvanians at all stages of their lives, with this budget, the legislature has failed to act on some of the most urgent problems facing communities across the Commonwealth, including the high costs of energy, the critical need for transit funding, and the ongoing housing crisis.\nHARRISBURG, PA − July 13, 2026 −\nToday, following the Pennsylvania General Assembly’s passage of the 2026–2027 state budget during a special session that spanned the weekend,\nState Senator Nikil Saval (D–Philadelphia)\nissued the following statement:\n“In communities across the country and throughout our Commonwealth, people have been loud, clear, and uncompromising in their demands for their government to prioritize their needs over the profits of the billionaires, wealthy CEOs, and big corporations that exploit our labor and our lands. This year’s budget makes strides to support Pennsylvanians at all moments of their lives—increased money to retain childcare workers, more funding for education and investments in teachers and staff, money back in the pockets of Pennsylvanians working hard to make ends meet, and additional funding for nursing homes. This budget also saw a crucial policy win that I have championed alongside Senator Hughes for years: the creation of a public database to help track and preserve Pennsylvania’s affordable housing.\n“But to truly meet this moment of incredible financial hardship, Pennsylvanians need their representatives to be just as loud, clear, and uncompromising as they are.\n“The General Assembly has deferred action to combat high energy costs. Instead of regulating the development of data centers, our government continues recklessly to incentivize it—their proliferation across the Commonwealth emerging as a key obstacle to our transition away from a fossil fuel economy.\n“The General Assembly has deferred action to invest fully in public transit. Despite the continued activation and involvement of tens of thousands of Pennsylvanians in urban, suburban, and rural counties alike calling for full, permanent funding for public transit, we will once again face this issue in 2027, when our timeline has become much more urgent.\n“The General Assembly has deferred action to address a housing crisis that worsens each year. Nearly one in three Pennsylvania households is cost burdened, and our Commonwealth has a deficit of nearly 100,000 homes. With the passage of the 21st Century ROAD to Housing Act into law, the federal government has succeeded in advancing a nationwide pilot program for Whole-Home Repairs; our General Assembly has, again, failed to reinvest in its own hallmark initiative.\n“This budget could have moved the needle on some of the most pressing issues of our times; instead, this is a budget of missed opportunity. We will not let this opportunity pass us again. In the coming year, we will move to tax billionaires and wealthy corporations. We will fully and permanently fund transit agencies across the Commonwealth. We will identify and advance new streams of revenue capable of building the flourishing, resourced communities that our people need and deserve.”\n###\nPennsylvania State Senator Nikil Saval is a father, husband, writer, and organizer representing Pennsylvania’s First Senatorial District, which runs through the heart of Philadelphia. Saval serves as Democratic Chair of the Senate’s Urban Affairs & Housing Committee and leads the Senate’s Philadelphia Delegation. He’s dedicated to a Pennsylvania that works for everyone.",
    "ai_summary": {
      "summary": "Senator Nikil Saval issued a statement responding to the Pennsylvania General Assembly's passage of the 2026–2027 state budget. He acknowledged some positive elements, including increased childcare, education, and nursing home funding, and noted passage of a housing database policy he co-sponsored. He also criticized the legislature for failing to address energy costs, public transit funding, and the housing crisis, and pledged to pursue those issues in the coming year.",
      "action_type": "statement",
      "topics": [
        "housing",
        "infrastructure",
        "economy"
      ],
      "spin_flag": true
    }
  },
  {
    "title": "Senator Saval Secures Nearly $29 Million for Philadelphia Organizations and Institutions",
    "url": "https://pasenatorsaval.com/senator-saval-secures-nearly-29-million-for-philadelphia-organizations-and-institutions/",
    "date": null,
    "raw_text": "Senator Saval Secures Nearly $29 Million for Philadelphia Organizations and Institutions\nJuly 22, 2026\nGrants announced today will support arts and cultural projects, affordable housing and jobs creation initiatives, mission-driven service organizations, and vibrant community hubs that help position Philadelphia as a flourishing city for residents and visitors alike.\nPHILADELPHIA, PA\n−\nJuly 22, 2026 −\nToday\nState Senator Nikil Saval\n(D–Philadelphia) announced $28,652,644 in grants for capital projects to organizations and institutions throughout Pennsylvania’s First Senatorial District, which runs through the heart of Philadelphia. These grants are awarded through the\nRedevelopment Assistance Capital Program\n(RACP), a Commonwealth grant program administered by the state’s Office of the Budget.\n“Philadelphia’s greatest strength lies its communities,” said\nSenator Saval\n. “When we invest in the people and places that make our city so utterly special, we’re fortifying our region for everyone who makes their home here. I’m incredibly proud to have supported this investment of public dollars into cultivating green spaces, supporting singular arts initiatives, and expanding the capacity of devoted service organizations, as well as welcoming new projects that will bring housing and employment opportunities to our neighbors.”\nThe full list of award recipients and projects funded in the First Senatorial District is as follows:\nArch Street Meeting House\n—$125,000 awarded for new electrical service to support an upgraded fire suppression system, protecting the safety and integrity of the more than 200-year-old meetinghouse for its community and the visitors it serves.\nThe Attic Youth Center\n—$2,500,000 awarded for the complete renovation of The Attic Youth Center’s new home on Chestnut Street, allowing the organization to expand its services in meeting the needs of LGBTQ youth and their families who travel throughout the region and the country for The Attic’s community and support.\nFolk Arts-Cultural Treasures (FACTS) Charter School\n—$250,000 awarded for the revitalization of FACTS’s newly acquired facilities, meeting the needs of its growing community of K–8th grade students with an exemplary education that utilizes traditional arts and cultures from their own and neighboring communities.\nThe Franklin Institute\n—$2,000,000 awarded for the replacement of the Franklin Institute’s end-of-life electrical switchgear, increasing its capacity to bring world-class exhibits to Philadelphia residents and visitors.\nFranklin Square Playground\n—$1,000,000 awarded for the reconstruction of Franklin Square’s 12,500-square-foot playground to make it safer, more welcoming, and more accessible for all children who visit the square.\nHuntingdon Bank Building\n—$1,000,000 awarded for the revitalization of the historic Huntingdon Bank to meet the contemporary needs of a busy commercial corridor while preserving the architectural integrity of the building.\nJoin or Die Bench\n—$250,000 awarded for a stone sculpture interpreting Benjamin Franklin’s iconic cartoon of a segmented snake representing the colonies. The sculpture will offer permanent seating and play elements across from the Liberty Bell Pavilion.\nKimmel Center\n—$2,000,000 awarded for extensive internal and external upgrades to the Kimmel Center, ensuring the integrity of the renowned arts facility and enhancing the experience of performers and audience members alike.\nLiguori Academy\n—$500,000 awarded for renovations to the electrical and ventilation systems of the Liguori Academy’s building trades learning center, allowing youth to participate in hands-on training leading to pre-apprenticeship certification.\nMarian Anderson Field\n—$750,000 awarded for the redevelopment of the beloved and well-used field at the Marian Anderson Recreation Center, providing a safe and accessible outdoor recreation space.\nMinistry of Awe\n—$125,000 awarded for the redevelopment of the historic Manufacturers National Bank as an immersive art and story experience in the heart of Old City, inviting creativity and connection while preserving the unique architectural features of the Frank Furness-designed building.\nMonell Center\n—$500,000 awarded for the creation of a transformative life sciences hub on Philadelphia’s North Broad Street corridor, supporting advanced public health research and community programs in science, health, and wellbeing with state-of-the-art facilities.\nNarrows Restaurant\n—$1,500,000 awarded for the transformation of two adjacent properties on Rittenhouse Square into a world-class dining destination, featuring a multi-floor restaurant with an open kitchen, group dining areas, and a dedicated sweets room.\nPenns Landing Park Pavilion\n—$2,000,000 awarded for the creation of a sweeping central pavilion to serve as the focal point and anchoring space of the new Penn’s Landing Park, offering a welcoming gateway to Philadelphia’s Delaware River waterfront.\nPhiladelphia Eagles Training Facility\n—$4,000,000 awarded for renovations that will expand locker rooms and training facilities for Eagles players, coaches, and staff and expand and renovate the cafeteria with additional capacity, including a rooftop area for guests.\nPhiladelphia Sports Complex\n—$1,402,644 awarded for an operations center within the Sports Complex, including a video wall, workstations, conference rooms, offices, and all back-of-house facilities, expanding the capacity for workers and visitors alike.\nPhilly House Dining Hall\n—$500,000 awarded for upgrades to Philly House’s kitchen and the expansion of its dining hall, increasing the capacity and reach of its 365-day free meal services for Philadelphians in need.\nPhiladelphia Youth Orchestra\n—$1,000,000 awarded for renovations to Philadelphia Youth Orchestra’s Saint Patrick Hall, enhancing accessibility and increased capacity through the creation of high-quality artistic spaces.\nRhoads Industries\n—$4,000,000 awarded for the construction of a new waterfront building, making way for the construction of a large-scale fabrication high-bay manufacturing center, bringing jobs and innovation to Philadelphia’s Navy Yard.\nSheet Metal Workers Local 19\n—$2,000,000 awarded for the modernization of the Sheet Metal Workers Local 19 Union Hall, upgrading the well-used space that anchors community activity and connection.\nSuperfit\n—$500,000 awarded for renovations to Superfit’s new facilities in Society Hill, supporting the continued presence of a hyperlocal manufacturer.\nVillage of Industry and Art\n—$500,000 awarded for the restoration of historic Hamilton Hall, part of the former University of the Arts campus, as VIA, honoring the legacy of community and art on South Broad Street. Facilities will include long-term affordable artist studios; workspaces for small businesses, makers, and mission-driven organizations; and venues for performances, exhibitions, and community programming.\nWinter West Revitalization\n—$250,000 awarded for the construction of affordable housing in Philadelphia’s beloved Chinatown, repurposing the former 6th Police District Office into green, energy-efficient units and activating the 11th and Winter Street corridor to anchor working families.\nTo receive Senator Saval’s support, grant applicants must demonstrate the benefit their project provides to the City of Philadelphia and communities throughout the First Senatorial District. Senator Saval’s office meets with individual grant applicants and thoroughly reviews project plans and overall funding commitments as part of their extensive consideration of each application.\nSenator Saval is committed to collaborating with local partners to foster enduring state investment in communities throughout the First Senatorial District. For information or help navigating state grant and award programs, please\ncontact his office\n.\nRACP awards are granted for the acquisition and construction of regional economic, cultural, civic, recreational, and historical improvement projects. For more information about RACP awards, including application information and a full list of current recipients, please visit the\nOffice of the Budget’s website\n.",
    "ai_summary": {
      "summary": "Senator Nikil Saval announced that 23 Philadelphia-area organizations and institutions will receive a combined $28.65 million in state capital grants through Pennsylvania's Redevelopment Assistance Capital Program (RACP). The grants, administered by the state Office of the Budget, will fund construction, renovation, and equipment projects ranging from affordable housing and job training facilities to arts venues and sports infrastructure. Saval's role was to review and support applications from organizations in his district, not to directly allocate or control the funds.",
      "action_type": "other",
      "topics": [
        "economy",
        "housing",
        "education"
      ],
      "spin_flag": true
    }
  }
]